#Which city has the highest number of restaurants?
In [91]:
city_data = df['area'].dropna()

restaurants_count_by_city = city_data.value_counts()

highest_restaurants_city = restaurants_count_by_city.idxmax()

restaurants_count_by_city.plot(kind='bar', edgecolor='black')
plt.title('Number of Restaurants in Each City')
plt.xlabel('City')
plt.ylabel('Number of Restaurants')
plt.show()

print(f"The city with the highest number of restaurants is: {highest_restaurants_city}")

The city with the highest number of restaurants is: Byresandra,Tavarekere,Madiwala

#How does the rating correlate with the average cost for two people?
In [121]:
correlation_data = df[['rate (out of 5)', 'avg cost (two people)']].dropna()
correlation_data['Average Cost for two'] = correlation_data['avg cost (two people)'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='rate (out of 5)', y='avg cost (two people)', data=correlation_data)
plt.title('Correlation Between Rating and Average Cost for Two')
plt.xlabel('Aggregate Rating')
plt.ylabel('Average Cost for Two')
plt.show()

# which area has the highest number of highlyrated restaurants (rating > 4.5)?
In [126]:
highly_rated_data =df[['local address', 'rate (out of 5)']].dropna()

highly_rated_data = highly_rated_data[highly_rated_data['rate (out of 5)'] > 4.5]
highly_rated_counts = highly_rated_data['local address'].value_counts()


highest_rated_locality = highly_rated_counts.idxmax()

print(f"The area with the highest number of highly-rated restaurants (rating > 4.5) is: {highest_rated_locality}")

The area with the highest number of highly-rated restaurants (rating > 4.5) is: Whitefield
